The paper deals with the problem of assigning traffic in an urban road network infrastructure, which involves strategic behavior of drivers. This suggests that the paper is likely to belong to the Game Theory (cs.GT) sub-category. Additionally, the paper proposes moneyless mechanisms that are resilient to manipulation by the agents, which indicates that it may also belong to the Artificial Intelligence (cs.AI) sub-category. The paper also uses empirical testing to evaluate the proposed mechanisms, which suggests that it may belong to the Machine Learning (cs.LG) sub-category. Furthermore, the paper deals with multi-agent systems and coordination, which suggests that it may also belong to the Multi-Agent Systems (cs.MA) sub-category. Finally, the paper deals with optimization and approximation guarantees, which suggests that it may also belong to the Social and Information Networks (cs.SI) sub-category.
